      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Why job searches fail without a strategy</h2>
      <p>The most common job search failure mode is not laziness — it is volume without targeting. Professionals apply to 50–100 roles with the same resume, the same LinkedIn profile, and the same generic cover letter, and interpret the lack of response as a market problem. Usually it is a positioning problem.</p>
      <p>A targeted job search with strong positioning — the right roles, the right resume, the right LinkedIn signal, and deliberate outreach — typically generates more interviews from 20 strategic applications than from 200 undifferentiated ones.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">The Askia job search system</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Role targeting:</strong> Identify the exact titles, levels, and companies where your background has the highest conversion probability</li>
        <li><strong>Positioning:</strong> Rebuild your resume and LinkedIn to signal the right level and generate inbound</li>
        <li><strong>Outreach:</strong> Build a structured networking and direct outreach system that bypasses the application black hole</li>
        <li><strong>Pipeline management:</strong> Track, prioritize, and advance conversations with discipline</li>
        <li><strong>Interview conversion:</strong> Prepare for the specific interviews in your pipeline, not generic prep</li>
        <li><strong>Offer strategy:</strong> Negotiate compensation from a position of clarity and leverage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

